body:
I used protect-lib mode for cosim. 
TB is too complex, so vcs/xcelium could be used to handle that, while DUT is handled by verilator.

Unfortuantely, by default waveform dump is not enabled.

With little change, It actually can.

I write one time.cpp file to define sc_time_stamp() and enable traceEverOn.

```c
#include "svdpi.h"
#include "vpi_user.h"

typedef unsigned long long ullong;

extern "C" {
void traceon() {
     Verilated::traceEverOn(true);
}

ullong edahub_time() {
    static s_vpi_time t = {vpiSimTime, 0, 0, 0.0};
    uint64_t simtime;
    vpi_get_time(0, &t); 
    simtime = (((uint64_t)t.high <<32)|t.low);
    printf("time = %llu\n", simtime);
    return simtime;
}

int edahub_time_precision(){
  return vpi_get(vpiTimePrecision, 0); 
}


}

// Called by $time in Verilog
double sc_time_stamp() {
    return static_cast<double>(edahub_time());
}
```

in original DUT file, I add

```verilog
initial begin
  $display("[%0t] Tracing to logs/vlt_dump.vcd...\n", $time);
  $dumpfile("logs/vlt_dump.vcd");
  $dumpvars();
  $display("[%0t] Model running...\n", $time);
end
```

This solution will cause one re-dump issue.
```
%Warning: previous dump at t=131149, requesting t=131149, dump call ignored
```

The issue is caused by the evals in wrapper file for comb and sequential logic.

Don't know if there is solution to avoid this.

in C code, actually I want to get VerilatedVcd object, then use its member function set_time_resolution to set the time precision (as you see, I already use vip to get time precision (in edahub_time_precision).

I also tried to compile the DUT in non-protect-lib mode. Then I write one wrapper by myself to call eval(). With this method, I could create VerilatedVcd object and do anything I want.
